Winter\
Winter is a quiet time.\
Also, a time of waiting\'85 for spring shearing, April lambs and spring grass. \
Its a wonderful opportunity to spend closeup time with the sheep. When the sheep are out grazing in the pasture they are focused on eating! .\
Sheep are hardy, but need access to shelter during winter snow, rain and wind storms. The greenhouse barn provides shelter with plenty of ventilation and light.\
Attached to the 24\'92 x 21\'92 greenhouse barn is a 16\'92 x 16\'92 fenced paddock where the ewes can be outside in good weather. \
In mid-November, Angelo the ram is introduced to the ewes to be bred.\
The ram is with the ewes for 32 days (two, seventeen--day cycles.) Gestation is five months, with lambs arriving in mid-April when the grass is beginning to grow. Fresh grass is important for the lactating ewes, so they have plenty of nutritious milk for their lambs.\
The ram is \'93half the flock,\'94 so it is important he is healthy and well-bred. \
Rams and ram lambs are kept separate from the ewes. They have their own simple lean-to shelter attached to one of the small hay sheds. Covered with greenhouse plastic, it is \'93like being outdoors,\'94 yet provides ventilation and protection from winter winds, snow and rain.\
