\f2\i\fs54 \cf0 Lambs on Grass\
\pard\pardeftab720\ri-1440\sl288\slmult1

\f0\i0\fs24 \cf0 It is vital the ewe and lambs establish a strong nursing relationship. \
The lambs will grow and thrive if \uc0\u8232 they are efficient strong nursers.\
\
At about two weeks old, lambs have access to an outdoor pasture during the day. They learn to stay together as a flock, to keep track of mom, and to stay away from the electric fence.\
\
Sheep eat grass with vigor and energy. They eat a lot of grass, especially lactating ewes. Sheep usually eat, chew cud or rest as a group. Any behavior, such as sitting down, or not staying with the flock, when all are eating may indicate a sick or injured sheep.\
\
Top and left photos show sheep just moved to new grass. In front is grass they grazed the day before.\
\
To fully develop their rumens, it is important that lambs have access to enough forage. A well-developed rumen will support their growth, and in the coming years pregnancies and lactations.\
